We are given the volume of a cone.

\begin{align*}V = \frac13 \pi r^2 h\end{align*}

If we differentiate this expression as it is, we will end up with an
expression relating $dV/dt$ to both variables of \emph{r} and \emph{h}.
To avoid this, we need to write the volume formula in terms of just
\emph{r} or \emph{h}, by writing one variable in terms of another. The
question states that the length of the stalagmite is always five times
its radius, so we can write $h  = 5r$, or, alternatively, $r = h/5$.

\emph{(i) Finding an expression in terms of h}: Using $r = h/5$, we plug
it into our volume formula to get

\begin{align*}
V &= \frac13 \pi \left(\frac{h}{5}\right)^2 h\\
&= \frac13 \pi \frac{h^3}{25} \end{align*}

Differentiating yields

\begin{align*}
\frac{dV}{dt} &= \frac13 \pi \frac{3h^2}{25}\frac{dh}{dt}\\
&= \frac{\pi h^2}{25} \frac{dh}{dt} \end{align*}

And because we know that $dh/dt = 0.13$ mm/year, we finally reach an
expression relating the rate of change in volume to the height \emph{h}

\begin{align*}\frac{dV}{dt} = \frac{\pi h^2}{25} 0.13\end{align*}

\emph{(ii) Finding an expression in terms of r}: To find an expression
in terms of \emph{r} we simply use the relationship \emph{h = 5r} to get

\begin{align*}
V &= \frac13 \pi r^2 (5r)\\
&= \frac53 \pi r^3 \end{align*}

Differentiating yields

\begin{align*}
\frac{dV}{dt} &= \frac53 \pi 3r^2 \frac{dr}{dt}\\
&= 5\pi r^2\frac{dr}{dt} \end{align*}

To find an expression for $dV/dt$ solely in terms of $r$, we need to
find $dr/dt$. We can do this by differentiating the equation $h = 5r$ to
get

\begin{align*}\frac{dh}{dt} = 5\frac{dr}{dt}\end{align*}

\begin{align*}\frac{0.13}{5} = \frac{dr}{dt}\end{align*}

Plugging this into our formula for $dV/dt$ gives

\begin{align*}\frac{dV}{dt} &= 5\pi r^2 \frac{0.13}{5} \\
&= \pi 0.13 r^2\end{align*}

in terms of \emph{r}, as desired.
